<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level CREATE ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_manager` UNCONDITIONAL create access
    on records of the `x_casemgmt_case_party` custom table inside the scoped
    application `x_casemgmt`. This is the CREATE companion to the case_manager
    read / write / delete ACLs on the case_party table whose granting ACLs are
    materialized by the sibling files:
        - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_read_agent_assigned.xml
          (manager reads via the same broader ACL pattern: read-all is
          granted to manager, read-assigned to agent - the agent-assigned
          ACL also lists manager so the union grants manager unconditional
          read access)
        - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_write_agent_assigned.xml
          (similar union: manager + agent-assigned)
        - ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_delete_manager.xml
          (only manager can delete; agent and viewer denied by absence)
    Together those four files realize the AAP Section 0.5.6 manager row
    mirrored at the case_party table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
    "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_*.xml"
    ("Mirror ACL pattern at party level"):
        | Role                    | Create | Read | Write | Delete |
        | x_casemgmt_case_manager  |  Yes   | All  |  All  |  Yes   |

    Of the four CRUD operations, CREATE is the "entry-point" privilege for
    the case_party domain: it is the operation that brings new
    x_casemgmt_case_party rows into existence so that every downstream
    privilege (read, write, delete) and every downstream UI Policy guard -
    in particular the AAP Section 0.5.7 / 0.4.3 polymorphic
    party_type=Person|Organization rule encoded in
    ../ui_policy/x_casemgmt_case_party_conditional_fields.xml - has party
    records to act upon. Without this ACL no x_casemgmt_case_manager-tier
    user could file a new party association against an existing case from
    the internal native form view's Related List for case_party (per AAP
    Section 0.4.4 "Related Lists on the case form for both case_task and
    case_party"), and the manager would be reduced to a
    read/write/delete-only role on party records originating elsewhere
    (specifically: agent-originated parties). That outcome would directly
    contradict the AAP Section 0.5.6 "Create=Yes" cell for the manager row
    mirrored to the case_party table, and it would also break the
    operational pattern in which a manager opens a case, immediately
    associates one or more parties (Requester, Respondent, Witness, etc.
    via the role_label String(100) field per AAP Section 0.5.7 case_party
    table contract), and routes any resulting tasks to case_agent
    assignees through ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_manager.xml.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_manager row, mirrored at the
        case_party table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_*.xml"
        ("Mirror ACL pattern at party level"):
            | Role                    | Create | Read | Write | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_manager  |  Yes   | All  |  All  |  Yes   |
        This file authors the single "Create = Yes" cell of the manager
        row for the case_party table. The "All" Read cell is authored by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_read_agent_assigned.xml (which lists
        BOTH manager and agent in its <roles> field so a single ACL
        covers the union of unconditional manager-read and conditional
        agent-read); the "All" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_write_agent_assigned.xml (similar
        union pattern); the "Yes" Delete cell by
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_delete_manager.xml (manager-only).
        Each row of the ACL matrix maps to exactly one or zero ACL XML
        files - this per-cell granularity is what lets the Update Set
        add or remove role privileges independently without entangling
        roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - all-roles create coverage on
        x_casemgmt_case_party:
            - case_manager: Create=Yes -> THIS FILE
            - case_agent:   Create=Yes -> ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_create_agent.xml
                                          (also unconditional; per AAP
                                           both manager and agent can
                                           create party associations)
            - case_viewer:  Create=No  -> deliberate absence of any
                                          x_casemgmt_case_party_create_viewer.xml
                                          (deny-by-default: ServiceNow
                                          record-level ACLs are deny-by-
                                          default; a role with no granting
                                          ACL for an operation cannot
                                          perform that operation)
        Together these three facts implement the user prompt's contract
        that managers (operational oversight tier) and agents (operational
        worker tier) can both originate party-association records, while
        the lowest-privilege viewer (audit / compliance / supervisor tier
        with read-only access) cannot. The agent's create is paired with
        read/write _agent_assigned restrictions that limit the agent's
        subsequent visibility of and edits to their own creations to
        "Assigned only" rows (where the parent case has assigned_agent =
        current user OR assigned_group contains current user per AAP
        Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only" definition); the manager has no
        such post-create restriction (manager Read=All, Write=All,
        Delete=Yes on case_party).
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
            "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write;
             case_agent cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager
             has full access."
        The clause "case_manager has full access" requires that the
        manager role be able to perform every CRUD operation on the
        case_party table; of the four operations, CREATE is the
        operation that brings new rows into the domain. This ACL
        satisfies that clause for the create operation on the party
        domain; the parallel clauses about case_viewer (no write on
        case_party - enforced by absence of any case_party write/create/
        delete ACL listing case_viewer) and case_agent (no unassigned
        access - enforced by the scripted "Assigned only" condition in
        the read/write _agent_assigned ACLs) are unaffected by this ACL
        and are enforced by separate sibling ACL files.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's
        ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig map." This ACL is the
        table-level CREATE binding for the highest-tier scoped role on
        the party domain and is one of the declarative facts the
        platform's sys_security_acl evaluator consumes when authorizing
        a row insertion at runtime against the case_party table.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): "ApplicationRolesConfig + RolesPrivilegesService
        + URL-based privilege metadata -> scoped roles + ACLs." In
        ArkCase the equivalent of THIS file would have been TWO entries
        in the rolesToPrivileges map (because ArkCase modeled
        person-association and organization-association in TWO separate
        tables, acm_person_assoc and acm_person_org_assoc) binding the
        manager-equivalent role to create privilege identifiers such as
        `acm-person-association-create` and
        `acm-organization-association-create`, evaluated at HTTP request
        time by AcmPluginUrlPrivilege against the POST verb on the
        person plugin's REST endpoints (e.g., the
        OrganizationAssociationAPIController referenced in AAP
        Section 0.2.1.3). The ServiceNow target replaces both map
        bindings AND the URL-privilege evaluator with this single
        declarative ACL record - because the target's case_party table
        is polymorphic (party_type Choice = Person | Organization with
        conditional person and organization reference fields per AAP
        Section 0.4.3 Polymorphic association via single-table choice +
        UI Policy), one ACL governs create for both Person and
        Organization variants.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Polymorphic association via single-table choice +
        UI Policy): the case_party table collapses ArkCase's two
        separate association tables (acm_person_assoc,
        acm_person_org_assoc) into a single polymorphic ServiceNow
        table with a `party_type` Choice discriminator
        (Person | Organization). Because both polymorphic sub-shapes are
        stored in a single physical table, a single ACL record
        (this one) governs create access for the manager role across
        BOTH variants - there is no need for separate Person /
        Organization manager-create ACLs. This is a deliberate
        simplification of the source ArkCase model and is the same
        polymorphic-collapse pattern realized by every other ACL on the
        case_party table.
      - Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping, x_casemgmt_case_party):
        "case (Reference -> x_casemgmt_case, Mandatory), party_type
        (Choice: Person, Organization), person (Reference -> sys_user,
        Conditional: required if party_type = Person), organization
        (Reference -> core_company, Conditional: required if party_type
        = Organization), role_label (String(100), Mandatory)." A user
        with the case_manager role and this ACL grant can populate any
        valid combination of these five fields when inserting a new
        case_party row from the internal form. The mandatory-field
        enforcement on case (parent case reference), party_type, and
        role_label is implemented at the dictionary level by
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_case.xml,
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_party_type.xml, and
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_party_role_label.xml respectively;
        this ACL only governs WHO may attempt the insert, not WHAT the
        insert payload must contain.

    Why advanced=false (no scripted condition for create):
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6, the case_manager role's privileges are
      unconditional ("All", "Full access") - there is no "Assigned only"
      or other row-level filter. Therefore:
        - <advanced>false</advanced>      - no scripted condition
        - <condition/>                    - empty encoded query (no row filter)
        - <script/>                       - empty server-side script
      With no condition and no script, the ACL evaluates to "permit" for
      any caller who carries the x_casemgmt_case_manager role. This is the
      correct semantic for the AAP's "manager has full create" requirement.
      Setting advanced=true with an empty script would be functionally
      equivalent but stylistically incorrect - the ServiceNow convention
      is to reserve advanced=true for ACLs that actually carry a scripted
      body (e.g., the ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_read_agent_assigned.xml
      and ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_write_agent_assigned.xml siblings,
      which DO carry "Assigned only" filter scripts that traverse the
      case_party.case reference up to the parent case row to evaluate the
      AAP Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only" rule).

    Why CREATE is granted to manager (design rationale):
      - Operational responsibility: per AAP Section 0.5.6 the manager is
        the role tier that bears full responsibility for the case
        lifecycle; party associations are a fundamental part of every
        case's "who is involved" facts (per AAP Section 0.5.7 the
        role_label field captures values such as "Requester",
        "Respondent", "Witness"). Denying the manager the ability to
        create such associations would create the absurd situation of a
        manager who can read/write/delete party records but must wait
        for an agent to bring them into being.
      - Mirror parity with case and case_task tables: the manager has
        Create=Yes on x_casemgmt_case (per
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml) and Create=Yes on
        x_casemgmt_case_task (per
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_manager.xml). Granting
        Create=Yes on x_casemgmt_case_party preserves the manager's
        uniform "full access on every table" posture across all three
        custom tables in the scoped application.
      - Demo-data seeding: the synthetic seed-data files
        ../seed-data/parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml (per AAP
        Section 0.3.1 "at least one Person and one Organization party
        per demo case to exercise the polymorphic UI policy") rely on
        the demo manager user (per
        ../seed-data/users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml) being
        able to create case_party rows during round-trip-verification.
        Although the seed script
        ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js runs as admin (which bypasses ACLs
        via admin_overrides=true), post-seed smoke tests against the
        demo manager's authenticated session depend on this ACL being
        in force so that interactive party creation is verified end-to-
        end.
      - Polymorphic data integrity: because the case_party table is
        polymorphic (Person | Organization variants share one table per
        AAP Section 0.4.3), the manager's create privilege uniformly
        covers both polymorphic variants. The choice of which variant
        to populate (person ref vs organization ref) is a per-row
        decision driven by the Choice field party_type and enforced at
        the form level by the UI Policy
        ../ui_policy/x_casemgmt_case_party_conditional_fields.xml; this
        ACL does not gate the choice itself, only the act of bringing a
        new row into existence.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single
        configuration map (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`)
        keyed by the property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that
        model, a "manager-equivalent" role (e.g., ROLE_PERSON_MANAGER /
        ROLE_ORG_MANAGER) would have been associated with create
        privilege identifiers such as `acm-person-association-create`
        and `acm-organization-association-create` (one identifier per
        association table, since ArkCase used two separate tables). The
        ServiceNow target replaces this map-based privilege association
        with declarative, scoped record-level ACLs - this XML record is
        the direct equivalent of the union of those two ArkCase map
        cells: the (case_manager, CREATE) pairing on the polymorphic
        case_party domain that subsumes both Person and Organization
        variants.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in
        ArkCase (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`,
        `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        `removeRolesPrivileges(...)`). The role-name normalization
        logic (uppercase, whitespace -> underscore, periods -> double
        underscore, prepend ROLE_PREFIX from
        RolePrivilegesConstants.ROLE_PREFIX = "ROLE_") was applied at
        runtime to every role name before lookup. All of this Java
        service surface is replaced in the ServiceNow target by the
        platform's built-in sys_security_acl evaluator; no scripted
        privilege resolver is needed and no role-name normalization is
        performed because the target uses the ServiceNow-native role
        naming convention `x_casemgmt_<role>` (no ROLE_ prefix, no
        case mangling). THIS ACL governs the creation of CASE_PARTY
        RECORDS, not the creation of the role itself - role creation
        is handled by ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml
        (and the analogous role records for case_agent and case_viewer).

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package source =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case_party (not any OOB
        global table such as `task` or any sibling association table),
        and <roles> references the scoped role x_casemgmt_case_manager.
        There are zero global writes from this file.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by
        name / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The
        <sys_id> below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_case_party.create.case_manager", a stable
        canonical identifier for this exact ACL) and is not a
        cross-reference to any other record. Computing the sys_id
        deterministically guarantees the ACL is re-applyable / idempotent
        across fresh PDIs and round-trip Update Set previews per AAP
        Section 0.7.3 Gate 7 ("Update Set loads without errors on a
        fresh PDI instance").
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case_party`
        with NO dot. The case_party table - unlike the parent case
        table - has no field-level ACLs at all by AAP design; the
        case-table field-level ACLs on assigned_group / assigned_agent
        (../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml) have no
        case_party analog because case_party fields (party_type,
        person, organization, role_label, case) carry no role-based
        write restrictions per AAP Section 0.5.6.
      - Operation = create: corresponds exactly to the "Create = Yes"
        cell in the AAP matrix for the case_manager role mirrored to
        the case_party table.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or seed
        scoped data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the
        ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js script runs as admin and uses
        admin_overrides to bypass scoped ACLs when seeding). It does
        NOT widen case_manager privileges - non-admin managers see
        exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set
        commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above. The
        platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is
        empty; no row-level filter applies to manager creates (manager
        has "full" access, not "Assigned only"). For an INSERT operation
        a row-level pre-filter would in any case be meaningless because
        there is no pre-existing row to filter against; ServiceNow's
        platform ACL evaluator ignores the condition field entirely
        for operation=create.
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform
        skips it because advanced=false.
      - type = record: ServiceNow's type field distinguishes
        record-level ACLs from UI/REST/SOAP-flavored ACLs. CREATE is a
        record-level operation (it brings a new row into the table) and
        therefore type=record is the correct value.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_party.xml (resolves
          <name>x_casemgmt_case_party</name> by table name lookup at
          apply time)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_manager.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles> by role name lookup at
          apply time)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_manager.xml
          (the demo manager's create access during round-trip
          verification depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml (the
          demo party rows are inserted under the seeding context which
          runs as admin and uses admin_overrides; nevertheless the ACL
          must be present so post-seed manager-as-user smoke tests
          succeed)
      The deny-by-default sibling pair that this file works with:
        - x_casemgmt_case_party_create_viewer.xml (DOES NOT EXIST - by design)
      Adding that file would VIOLATE the AAP Section 0.5.6 matrix
      ("case_viewer Create=No") and MUST NOT be done by any future
      agent.

    Mirror relationship to ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_create_manager.xml,
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_create_manager.xml, and
    ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_party_delete_manager.xml:
      This file is the case_party-table analog of the manager-create
      ACLs already authored for the case and case_task tables, and is
      the create-operation analog of the manager-delete ACL already
      authored for the case_party table. The ONLY differences between
      this file and its sibling case_party_delete_manager.xml are:
        - <operation>        create  (vs delete)
        - <sys_id>           MD5("x_casemgmt_case_party.create.case_manager")
                                                   (vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case_party.delete.case_manager"))
        - <sys_update_name>  sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_party_create_manager
                                                   (vs sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_party_delete_manager)
        - <description>      references the create operation
                                                   (vs delete)
      All other fields (active, admin_overrides, advanced, condition,
      name, roles, script, sys_class_name, sys_created_by, sys_name,
      sys_package, sys_policy, sys_scope, type, audit timestamps) are
      byte-for-byte identical so that the manager's privilege is
      uniformly unconditional across every CRUD operation on every
      table in the scoped application as the AAP matrix mandates.

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention
    (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"); ServiceNow
    Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the scope id
    must be concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped
    application. The deterministic sys_id below is computed against
    the `casemgmt` literal and remains stable across re-imports onto
    fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Allows users with the x_casemgmt_case_manager role to create case_party records.</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case_party</name>
        <operation>create</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_manager</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>8aa70279954d55c853beac37e0cdb560</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case_party</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_party_create_manager</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
